The highest occupied molecular orbital and lowest unoccupied molecular orbital are often referred to as the HOMO and LUMO, respectively.
As a simple MO example, consider the electrons in a hydrogen molecule, H (see molecular orbital diagram), with the two atoms labelled H' and H".
The lowest-energy atomic orbitals, 1s' and 1s", do not transform according to the symmetries of the molecule.
Because the H molecule has two electrons, they can both go in the bonding orbital, making the system lower in energy (hence more stable) than two free hydrogen atoms.
As with H, the lowest energy atomic orbitals are the 1s' and 1s", and do not transform according to the symmetries of the molecule, while the symmetry adapted atomic orbitals do.
