HeH would have a slight energy advantage, but not as much as H + 2 He, so the molecule is very unstable and exists only briefly before decomposing into hydrogen and helium.
In general, we find that atoms such as He that have full energy shells rarely bond with other atoms.
Orbital interactions to produce bonding or antibonding orbitals in heteronuclear diatomics occur if there is sufficient overlap between atomic orbitals as determined by their symmetries and similarity in orbital energies.
In hydrogen fluoride HF overlap between the H 1s and F 2s orbitals is allowed by symmetry but the difference in energy between the two atomic orbitals prevents them from interacting to create a molecular orbital.
Overlap between the H 1s and F 2p orbitals is also symmetry allowed, and these two atomic orbitals have a small energy separation.
Since HF is a non-centrosymmetric molecule, the symmetry labels g and u do not apply to its molecular orbitals.
To obtain quantitative values for the molecular energy levels, one needs to have molecular orbitals that are such that the configuration interaction (CI) expansion converges fast towards the full CI limit.
One usually solves this problem by expanding the molecular orbitals as linear combinations of Gaussian functions centered on the atomic nuclei (see linear combination of atomic orbitals and basis set (chemistry)).
